<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>YAHOO TO SPIN OFF CORE BUSINESS</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> After months of preparation to spin off Yahooâs stake in Alibaba, the board decided to call off the deal and spin off its core Internet business instead,<br />
<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/12/10/technology/yahoo-alibaba-spinoff.html?ref=dealbook">Vindu Goel reports in The New York Times.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The board said it still believed the company would prevail in a tax dispute, but <b>fears about challenging a $10 billion tax bill were depressing Yahooâs stock price.</b> </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">So the direction of the transaction was reversed, leaving <b>one Yahoo with the stake in Alibaba and the other with everything else, including the stake in Yahoo Japan.</b> </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Marissa Mayer said she planned to stay and run Yahooâs core businesses. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The board had decided that <b>selling the company was not the right choice</b>. âIf someone came in today and made offers on what the core or operating business is worth today, it would probably be a lowball offer,â said Maynard Webb, the board chairman. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The change in approach will add at least a year and a host of complexities to an already difficult process. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This will give Ms. Mayer more time to improve Yahooâs business, but it will be difficult, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/12/10/business/dealbook/marissa-mayer-has-a-year-to-fulfill-yahoos-potential.html">Steven Davidoff Solomon writes in the Deal Professor column</a>. The announcement could make it harder to retain talent and attract customers. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>The gamble is probably worth it</b>, Mr. Solomon notes. Yahooâs user base is enormous and the board thinks it can be further monetized. There is much potential value. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The world may soon know what that value is <b>without the lucrative stake in Alibaba</b> â and it is not worthless, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/12/10/business/dealbook/how-to-value-yahoos-core-business.html?partner=rss&#038;emc=rss">Leslie Picker writes in DealBook.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Analysts value the core business based on five times projected earnings before interest, taxes, debt and amortization, giving Yahoo a market capitalization of <b>$4.6 billion, $13.2 billion including the value of the Yahoo Japan stake.</b> </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">If the transaction is taxed, the bill would be a lot smaller than for the original plan to spin off the Alibaba investment. Assuming a 41 percent tax rate, Yahoo would pay $5.4 billion in taxes â <b>a saving of about $8 billion</b>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And <b>who would buy</b> the core business if it was sold? <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/12/10/business/dealbook/possible-suitors-for-yahoo.html?ref=dealbook">Jennifer Saba at Breakingviews</a> writes that it could fit into Barry Dillerâs menagerie at IAC/InterActive. Or it might feel at home with AOL at Verizon.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Whatever uncertainty there is around Yahoo, Ms. Mayer is <b>still in the money</b> with the stock options in her 2014 pay package, <a href="//www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-12-09/marissa-mayer-s-unusual-options-buoy-her-pay-even-as-yahoo-falls">Bloomberg News reports</a>. The strike price on the options, the amount Ms. Mayer would have to pay to exercise an option and buy a share, was set 15 months earlier when the stock was much lower. Her 2014 options were granted on Feb. 27 with a strike price of $18.87, while the stock closed at $38.47. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The instruments would have generated $14 million if exercised at the close of trading on Tuesday. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Still, Ms. Mayerâs golden parachute or what she would collect if her employment were terminated after a sale of Yahoo has sunk to $35 million this year, from $157.9 million in December 2014.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>ATLASSIAN SETS I.P.O. AT $21</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Itâs been a difficult year for stock market debuts, but Atlassian is <b>finishing off the year on a high note</b>,<br />
<a HREF="//www.nytimes.com/2015/12/10/business/dealbook/atlassian-sets-its-ipo-at-21.html?ref=dealbook">Michael J. de la Merced reports in DealBook.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The company, which makes products intended to make life easier for software developers, priced its initial public offering at $21 a share, <b>above its expected price range of $19 to $20 and raising $462 million.</b> </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The company was valued at $4.38 billion, making it the <b>fifth-biggest company to go public</b> this year. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Its stock sale is a rare bright spot in a chilly market where even prominent companies have struggled to win the valuations they were after. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Neiman Marcus and Digicel both postponed their market debuts. <b>Those that made it to public markets faltered</b> â the average I.P.O. that priced this year fell 2.4 percent from its offer price. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Even high-flying tech companies are no exception. Shares in the payments company Square have slipped 8 percent since pricing. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Atlassian breaks the mold in several ways. It was <b>founded in Australia</b>, rather than Silicon Valley like many other tech âunicorns.â Unlike other software companies, it does not have a huge sales force, relying on word of mouth. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It also does not collect money from outside investors. It is <b>financed by its own profits</b> and has been profitable for the last three years. </p>
