<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>SENATE REPUBLICANS INTRODUCE BILL FOR PUERTO RICO RELIEF</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Senate Republicans introduced a bill to extend assistance to Puerto Rico, but <b>stopped short of embracing proposals from the Obama administration</b>,<br />
<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/12/10/business/senate-republicans-introduce-bill-for-puerto-rico-relief.html">Mary Williams Walsh reports in DealBook.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The measure would include up to <b>$3 billion in cash relief, a payroll tax break for residents and a new independent authority that could borrow for Puerto Rico with no taxpayer guarantee.</b> </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âConsistent with the views of Congress and the administration that there will be no âbailoutâ of Puerto Rico, the full faith and credit of the United States is not pledged for the payment of debt obligations issued by the authority,â the bill said. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It also called for all the states to <b>disclose the true financial condition of their government pension plans</b>. Currently, actuarial numbers are used and they can understate the planâs cost. Using fair-value numbers could help negotiations to divert money from bondholders toward pensions. It could also help identify other states with distressed pension systems. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The $3 billion of cash relief would <b>come from a public-health fund created under the Affordable Care Act</b>. The bill said the money was âunobligatedâ and could be repurposed. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Republican bill would also designate a âchief financial officerâ to advise the islandâs governor on the budget. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Lawmakers from both parties have been working toward a Jan. 1 deadline, when Puerto Rico owes <b>bond payments of as much as $902 million.</b> </p>
